WEBVTT

1
00:00:17.001 --> 00:00:21.001
<font color=#0080C0><b>*** Subtitles by dylux ***</b></font>

2
00:00:22.805 --> 00:00:24.807
<i>♪ (The Ronettes' "Be My Baby"
playing throughout) ♪</i>

3
00:02:01.946 --> 00:02:03.656
<i>(Radio announcer) Hi, everybody.
This is your Cousin Brucie.</i>

4
00:02:03.739 --> 00:02:06.242
<i>Whoa! Our summer romances
are in full bloom,</i>

5
00:02:06.325 --> 00:02:08.536
<i>and everybody but everybody
is in love,</i>

6
00:02:08.619 --> 00:02:11.747
<i>so here's a great song
from The Four Seasons.</i>

7
00:02:11.831 --> 00:02:13.833
<i>♪ ("Big Girls Don't Cry" playing) ♪</i>

8
00:02:19.088 --> 00:02:21.507
<i>(Baby) That was the summer of 1963,</i>

9
00:02:21.590 --> 00:02:23.509
<i>when everybody called me Baby,</i>

10
00:02:23.592 --> 00:02:25.469
<i>and it didn’t occur
to me to mind.</i>

11
00:02:34.478 --> 00:02:36.564
<i>That was before
President Kennedy was shot,</i>

12
00:02:36.647 --> 00:02:38.566
<i>before The Beatles came,</i>

13
00:02:38.649 --> 00:02:40.442
<i>when I couldn't wait
to join the Peace Corps,</i>

14
00:02:40.526 --> 00:02:43.654
<i>and I thought I'd never find
a guy as great as my Dad.</i>

15
00:02:44.822 --> 00:02:49.076
<i>♪ ("Big Girls Don't Cry"
continues playing) ♪</i>

16
00:02:54.206 --> 00:02:57.251
<i>That was the summer
we went to Kellerman's.</i>

17
00:03:15.936 --> 00:03:18.939
<i>(Stan on bullhorn)</i> Ping-Pong in the
west arcade, softball on the east diamond.

18
00:03:19.023 --> 00:03:21.275
All you Sandy Koufaxes,
get out there!

19
00:03:21.358 --> 00:03:22.818
Complimentary dance lessons
in the gazebo.

20
00:03:23.944 --> 00:03:26.488
Oh, my God. Look at that!

21
00:03:26.572 --> 00:03:30.701
Mom, I should've brought the coral shoes.
You said I was taking too much.

22
00:03:30.784 --> 00:03:33.454
Well, sweetheart,
you brought ten pairs.

23
00:03:33.537 --> 00:03:35.956
But the coral shoes
matched that dress.

24
00:03:36.040 --> 00:03:37.708
This is not a tragedy.

25
00:03:37.791 --> 00:03:40.044
A tragedy is three men
trapped in a mine

26
00:03:40.127 --> 00:03:42.254
or police dogs used
in Birmingham.

27
00:03:42.338 --> 00:03:44.590
Monks burning themselves
in protest.

28
00:03:44.673 --> 00:03:46.050
Butt out, Baby.

29
00:03:46.133 --> 00:03:49.845
Okay, we got horseshoes
on the south lawn in 15 minutes!

30
00:03:49.929 --> 00:03:52.890
We've got "Splish-Splash,"
the water class, down by the lake.

31
00:03:52.973 --> 00:03:56.560
We have the still life art class,
we got volleyball and croquet.

32
00:03:56.644 --> 00:03:59.104
And for you older folks,
we got sacks!

33
00:03:59.188 --> 00:04:01.857
<i>(Laughs)</i> Gotcha.

34
00:04:01.941 --> 00:04:03.025
Doc!

35
00:04:04.026 --> 00:04:05.236
Max!

36
00:04:05.319 --> 00:04:10.115
Well, Doc, after all these years
I finally got you up on my mountain.

37
00:04:10.199 --> 00:04:12.409
<i>(Chuckles)</i>
So how's the blood pressure, Max?

38
00:04:12.493 --> 00:04:15.955
I want you girls to know
if it were not for this man,

39
00:04:16.038 --> 00:04:17.873
I'd be standing here dead.

40
00:04:17.957 --> 00:04:21.126
- Billy, get the bags.
- Right away, Doc. Right away.

41
00:04:21.210 --> 00:04:24.171
I kept the best cabin
for you and your beautiful girls.

42
00:04:28.175 --> 00:04:30.344
Hey, thanks a lot.

43
00:04:30.427 --> 00:04:32.137
You want a job here?

44
00:04:32.221 --> 00:04:35.307
There's a merengue class in
the gazebo in the next few minutes,

45
00:04:35.391 --> 00:04:38.143
the greatest teacher.
Used to be a Rockette.

46
00:04:38.227 --> 00:04:42.189
It's his first real vacation
in six years, Max. Take it easy.

47
00:04:42.273 --> 00:04:45.150
Three weeks here,
it'll feel like a year.

48
00:04:45.234 --> 00:04:45.276
One, two, three, four!

49
00:04:45.276 --> 00:04:45.359
One, two, three, four!

50
00:04:45.359 --> 00:04:46.860
One, two, three, four!

51
00:04:46.944 --> 00:04:48.779
Stomp those grapes
and stomp some more!

52
00:04:48.862 --> 00:04:52.992
One, two, three, four!
Listen to the music!

53
00:04:53.075 --> 00:04:54.493
- One, two, three...
- Sorry.

54
00:04:54.576 --> 00:04:56.328
Move your caboose
and shake it loose!

55
00:04:56.412 --> 00:05:00.624
One, two, three, four!
Stomp those grapes!

56
00:05:00.708 --> 00:05:01.750
Whoo!

57
00:05:01.834 --> 00:05:04.628
<i>♪ (Merengue music playing) ♪</i>

58
00:05:04.712 --> 00:05:07.506
Now come on, men!
Follow me into a round robin!

59
00:05:08.549 --> 00:05:10.676
Ladies, the inner circle!

60
00:05:10.759 --> 00:05:12.094
<i>(Woman laughing)</i>

61
00:05:20.894 --> 00:05:22.438
Oh, come on, ladies!

62
00:05:22.521 --> 00:05:23.939
God wouldn't have given you maracas

63
00:05:24.023 --> 00:05:27.192
if he didn't want you
to shake them!

64
00:05:31.280 --> 00:05:34.033
Okay now, ladies,
when I say "stop,"

65
00:05:34.116 --> 00:05:37.911
you're gonna find the man
of your dreams.

66
00:05:37.995 --> 00:05:39.163
Stop!

67
00:05:41.165 --> 00:05:45.252
Now remember, he's the boss
on the dance floor, if nowhere else.

68
00:05:45.336 --> 00:05:47.129
<i>(Laughter)</i>

69
00:05:50.174 --> 00:05:52.176
<i>(Crickets chirping)</i>

70
00:05:54.136 --> 00:05:56.805
Mom, Dad, I'm going up
to the main house to look around.

71
00:06:35.010 --> 00:06:37.721
<i>(Max)</i> There are
two kinds of help here.

72
00:06:37.805 --> 00:06:39.973
You waiters are all college guys,

73
00:06:40.057 --> 00:06:42.935
and I went to Harvard
and Yale to hire you.

74
00:06:44.019 --> 00:06:46.980
And why did I do that? Why?

75
00:06:48.399 --> 00:06:51.193
I shouldn't have to remind you.
This is a family place.

76
00:06:51.276 --> 00:06:53.862
That means you keep your fingers
out of the water,

77
00:06:53.946 --> 00:06:57.324
your hair out of the soup, and show
the goddamn daughters a good time.

78
00:06:58.575 --> 00:06:59.576
All the daughters.

79
00:07:01.078 --> 00:07:02.329
Even the dogs.

80
00:07:03.330 --> 00:07:06.083
Schlepp 'em out to the terrace,
Show 'em the stars.

81
00:07:06.166 --> 00:07:08.460
- Romance 'em any way you want.
- Got that, guys?

82
00:07:08.544 --> 00:07:10.504
The thing to do--
Hey, hold it! Hold it.

83
00:07:12.423 --> 00:07:16.009
Well, if it isn't
the entertainment staff.

84
00:07:16.093 --> 00:07:18.429
Listen, wise ass,
you got your own rules.

85
00:07:18.512 --> 00:07:19.680
Dance with the daughters.

86
00:07:19.763 --> 00:07:23.392
Teach 'em the mambo, the cha-cha,
anything they pay for.

87
00:07:23.475 --> 00:07:26.228
But that's it. That's where it ends.

88
00:07:27.396 --> 00:07:31.400
No funny business, no conversations,
and keep your hands off!

89
00:07:33.986 --> 00:07:35.195
It's the same at all these places.

90
00:07:35.279 --> 00:07:37.656
Some ass in the woods,
maybe, but no conversation.

91
00:07:37.739 --> 00:07:39.533
- <i>(Waiters laugh)</i>
- Watch it, Rodriguez.

92
00:07:41.869 --> 00:07:43.996
You think you can keep that
straight, Johnny?

93
00:07:44.079 --> 00:07:45.789
What you can and
can't lay your hands on?

94
00:07:45.873 --> 00:07:47.499
- <i>(Light laugh)</i>
- <i>(Sighs)</i>

95
00:07:50.210 --> 00:07:52.588
You just put your pickle
on everybody's plate, college boy,

96
00:07:52.671 --> 00:07:54.256
and leave the hard stuff to me.

97
00:07:54.339 --> 00:07:55.924
<i>(Guys)</i> Whoa.

98
00:08:00.679 --> 00:08:03.098
Sit down, sit down and I'll
get you some wine.

99
00:08:04.099 --> 00:08:05.601
Thank you, Max.

100
00:08:06.685 --> 00:08:08.854
Ah...

101
00:08:08.937 --> 00:08:10.689
This is Dr. and Mrs. Houseman.

102
00:08:10.772 --> 00:08:14.818
Baby, Lisa, this is your waiter,
Robbie Gould.

103
00:08:14.902 --> 00:08:17.571
- Yale medical school.
- Uh-huh.

104
00:08:17.654 --> 00:08:21.533
Robbie, these people are my special
guests. Get them anything they want.

105
00:08:21.617 --> 00:08:23.410
- Enjoy.
- Thanks, Max.

106
00:08:28.290 --> 00:08:30.751
Oh, look at all
this leftover food.

107
00:08:30.834 --> 00:08:32.502
Are there still
starving children in Europe?

108
00:08:32.586 --> 00:08:35.297
- Try Southeast Asia, Ma.
- Oh, right.

109
00:08:35.380 --> 00:08:38.884
Robbie, Baby wants to send
her leftover pot roast to Southeast Asia,

110
00:08:38.967 --> 00:08:42.012
so anything we don't finish,
you wrap up.

111
00:08:42.095 --> 00:08:44.723
Max, our Baby's gonna
change the world.

112
00:08:44.806 --> 00:08:48.143
- And what are you gonna do, missy?
- Lisa's gonna decorate it.

113
00:08:48.227 --> 00:08:50.729
She already does.

114
00:08:52.314 --> 00:08:56.235
Doc, I want you to meet someone.
My grandson Neil.

115
00:08:56.318 --> 00:08:58.737
Goes to the Cornell School
of Hotel Management.

116
00:08:58.820 --> 00:09:01.990
Baby's starting Mount Holyoke
in the fall.

117
00:09:02.074 --> 00:09:03.617
Oh, great.

118
00:09:12.459 --> 00:09:14.044
Are you going to major
in English?

119
00:09:14.127 --> 00:09:17.547
No. Economics of
underdeveloped countries.

120
00:09:17.631 --> 00:09:21.051
- I’m going into the Peace Corps.
- After the final show,

121
00:09:21.134 --> 00:09:24.221
I'm going to Mississippi with
a couple of busboys, freedom ride.

122
00:09:33.772 --> 00:09:35.774
<i>(Shoes clicking)</i>

123
00:09:44.366 --> 00:09:46.952
<i>(Max) This is
our own Tito Suarez.</i>

124
00:09:47.035 --> 00:09:48.412
<i>(Applause)</i>

125
00:10:01.675 --> 00:10:03.343
<i>(Applause)</i>

126
00:10:28.618 --> 00:10:30.620
<i>(New song begins)</i>

127
00:10:34.166 --> 00:10:36.460
Mambo! Yeah! Come on!

128
00:10:43.842 --> 00:10:45.927
Who's that?

129
00:10:46.011 --> 00:10:48.472
Oh, <i>them.</i>
They're the dance people.

130
00:10:48.555 --> 00:10:51.516
They're here to keep
the guests happy.

131
00:11:14.206 --> 00:11:16.583
They shouldn't be showing off
with each other.

132
00:11:16.666 --> 00:11:18.335
That's not gonna sell lessons.

133
00:11:20.253 --> 00:11:21.922
- <i>(Woman) Wow!</i>
- <i>(People murmuring)</i>

134
00:12:20.230 --> 00:12:21.440
<i>(Mouthing)</i> Cut!

135
00:12:35.245 --> 00:12:37.789
- Hi, kids. Having fun?
- Yeah.

136
00:12:37.873 --> 00:12:39.583
Actually, I've gotta excuse myself.

137
00:12:39.666 --> 00:12:41.751
I'm in charge of the games tonight.

138
00:12:41.835 --> 00:12:44.504
Say, would you like to help me
get things started?

139
00:12:44.588 --> 00:12:46.339
<i>(Jake) Sure she would.</i>

140
00:12:46.423 --> 00:12:47.757
<i>(Laughing)</i>

141
00:12:48.884 --> 00:12:50.886
<i>(Sawing)</i>

142
00:12:53.680 --> 00:12:57.559
This'll only hurt for a minute.
You've got Blue Cross, right?

143
00:12:57.642 --> 00:12:59.394
<i>(Laughter continues)</i>

144
00:13:00.395 --> 00:13:02.022
<i>(Drumroll)</i>

145
00:13:05.150 --> 00:13:06.568
<i>(Fanfare plays)</i>

146
00:13:06.651 --> 00:13:09.613
- <i>(Applause)</i>
- Was that good for you?

147
00:13:09.696 --> 00:13:13.241
And for being such a good sport,
here you go!

148
00:13:13.325 --> 00:13:15.327
- <i>(People laughing)</i>
- <i>♪ (Music playing) ♪</i>

149
00:13:19.122 --> 00:13:21.833
You know, I finally met a girl
exactly like my mother.

150
00:13:21.917 --> 00:13:24.920
Dresses like her, acts like her.
So I brought her home.

151
00:13:25.003 --> 00:13:28.632
My father doesn't like her!
<i>(Laughing)</i>

152
00:13:28.715 --> 00:13:30.550
Go figure.

153
00:13:30.634 --> 00:13:30.675
<i>(Distant laughter and applause)</i>

154
00:13:51.029 --> 00:13:53.031
<i>♪ ("Where Are You Tonight"
by Mark Scola playing distantly) ♪</i>

155
00:13:59.788 --> 00:14:01.790
<i>(Music volume increases)</i>

156
00:14:19.516 --> 00:14:22.102
- Hi.
- How'd you get here?

157
00:14:22.185 --> 00:14:23.770
- I was taking a walk.
- Go back.

158
00:14:23.853 --> 00:14:25.146
- Let me help you.
- No.

159
00:14:25.230 --> 00:14:27.899
- What's up there?
- No guests allowed. House rules.

160
00:14:27.983 --> 00:14:29.484
Why don't you go back
to the playhouse?

161
00:14:29.568 --> 00:14:32.195
I saw you dancing
with the little boss man.

162
00:14:32.279 --> 00:14:34.739
<i>(Hums mockingly)</i>

163
00:14:37.242 --> 00:14:38.827
Can you keep a secret?

164
00:14:41.496 --> 00:14:44.040
Your parents would kill you.

165
00:14:44.124 --> 00:14:45.917
Max would kill me.

166
00:14:52.048 --> 00:14:55.051
<i>♪ ("Do You Love Me" by The Contours
playing throughout) ♪</i>

167
00:15:39.137 --> 00:15:40.513
Where'd they learn to do that?

168
00:15:41.556 --> 00:15:42.432
Where?

169
00:15:43.475 --> 00:15:46.186
I don't know. Kids are doing it
in their basements back home.

170
00:15:47.771 --> 00:15:49.022
Wanna try it?

171
00:15:50.565 --> 00:15:51.691
Come on, Baby.

172
00:15:51.775 --> 00:15:54.778
<i>♪ ("Do You Love Me"
continues playing) ♪</i>

173
00:16:29.521 --> 00:16:32.607
Can you imagine dancing like this
on the main floor,

174
00:16:32.691 --> 00:16:35.068
home of the family fox-trot?

175
00:16:35.151 --> 00:16:37.320
Max would close the place down first.

176
00:16:39.406 --> 00:16:40.990
<i>(All cheering)</i>

177
00:17:09.894 --> 00:17:12.939
That's my cousin, Johnny Castle.

178
00:17:13.022 --> 00:17:15.191
He got me the job here.

179
00:17:15.275 --> 00:17:17.277
<i>("Do You Love Me" continues)</i>

180
00:17:34.043 --> 00:17:36.796
- They look great together.
- Yeah.

181
00:17:36.880 --> 00:17:39.340
You'd think they were
a couple, wouldn't you?

182
00:17:39.424 --> 00:17:43.136
- Aren't they?
- No, not since we were kids.

183
00:18:22.842 --> 00:18:25.303
- <i>(Man)</i> Do you love me?
- <i>(All cheering)</i>

184
00:18:25.386 --> 00:18:28.389
<i>♪ ("Love Man" by Otis Redding
starts playing) ♪</i>

185
00:18:44.489 --> 00:18:47.909
Yo, cuz, what's she doing here?

186
00:18:47.992 --> 00:18:50.703
She came with me.
She's with me.

187
00:18:50.787 --> 00:18:52.622
I carried a watermelon.

188
00:18:58.336 --> 00:19:00.129
"I carried a watermelon"?

189
00:19:00.213 --> 00:19:02.799
<i>♪ ("Love Man" continues playing) ♪</i>

190
00:19:34.205 --> 00:19:36.833
Bend your knees. Down.

191
00:19:41.045 --> 00:19:42.797
Watch. Watch my eyes.

192
00:19:43.798 --> 00:19:44.799
Good.

193
00:19:49.304 --> 00:19:50.346
That's better.

194
00:19:55.977 --> 00:19:57.729
Good. Now roll this way.

195
00:19:59.564 --> 00:20:00.773
Now watch.

196
00:20:11.200 --> 00:20:12.660
Look.

197
00:20:23.671 --> 00:20:25.256
<i>(All, singing along)</i>
<i>♪ Love man! ♪</i>

198
00:20:41.189 --> 00:20:42.857
<i>(Cheering and whooping)</i>

199
00:21:01.084 --> 00:21:04.545
<i>(Stan on bullhorn)</i> Ladies,
join our hair-raising wig show.

200
00:21:04.629 --> 00:21:09.342
Try your Sandra Dee, Jackie Kennedy,
or Elizabeth Taylor <i>Cleopatra</i> wig.

201
00:21:09.425 --> 00:21:12.929
- I’ll knock with three.
- Look at that cute fella.

202
00:21:13.012 --> 00:21:14.430
Look at these hands.
They're golden hands.

203
00:21:14.514 --> 00:21:17.892
<i>(Chattering indistinct)</i>

204
00:21:17.975 --> 00:21:20.937
My God, it's Cleopatra!
I feel like such an "asp...

205
00:21:21.020 --> 00:21:23.272
You look ten years younger.

206
00:21:23.356 --> 00:21:26.234
<i>(Stan)</i> At 10:15, by the pool,
we have calisthenics.

207
00:21:26.317 --> 00:21:29.654
Then on the west porch, we have
a symposium by Rabbi Maurice Sherman

208
00:21:29.737 --> 00:21:32.073
on the psychology of insult comedians.

209
00:21:32.156 --> 00:21:34.283
<i>(Wheezy laughter)</i>

210
00:21:34.367 --> 00:21:37.370
So I say, "Ask not what
your waiter can do for you,

211
00:21:37.453 --> 00:21:39.914
but what you can do
for your waiter."

212
00:21:39.997 --> 00:21:42.709
You know, if tips keep up, I'll have
enough for my Alfa Romeo.

213
00:21:44.377 --> 00:21:46.421
That's my favorite car.

214
00:21:48.381 --> 00:21:50.383
Ladies, you look very lovely.

215
00:21:51.968 --> 00:21:53.845
Baby, would you cover
for me tonight?

216
00:21:53.928 --> 00:21:55.555
Tell Mommy and Daddy
I went to lie down.

217
00:21:55.638 --> 00:21:59.225
- Where are you going?
- To the golf course.

218
00:21:59.308 --> 00:22:01.686
There's a pretty view
from the first tee.

219
00:22:04.939 --> 00:22:06.774
Good. Thanks.

220
00:22:14.115 --> 00:22:16.409
So you were really a Rockette?

221
00:22:17.410 --> 00:22:19.704
I think you're a wonderful dancer.

222
00:22:19.787 --> 00:22:22.915
Yeah? Well, my mother
kicked me out when I was 16.

223
00:22:22.999 --> 00:22:24.834
I've been dancing ever since.

224
00:22:24.917 --> 00:22:26.919
It's the only thing
I ever wanted to do anyway.

225
00:22:28.045 --> 00:22:29.422
I envy you.

226
00:22:29.505 --> 00:22:31.382
- <i>(Scoffs)</i>
- <i>(Latches click)</i>

227
00:22:37.722 --> 00:22:39.724
<i>(Distant music playing)</i>

228
00:22:54.071 --> 00:22:56.991
- Aren't you dancing, Doc?
- We're waiting for a waltz.

229
00:22:57.074 --> 00:22:58.117
Ah.

230
00:22:59.410 --> 00:23:03.664
Hi, Max. Aren't my dance lessons
starting to pay off?

231
00:23:03.748 --> 00:23:07.251
You look great, Vivian!
Terrific!

232
00:23:10.505 --> 00:23:14.383
That's Vivian Pressman,
one of the bungalow bunnies.

233
00:23:15.968 --> 00:23:18.638
That's what we call the women
who stay here all week long.

234
00:23:19.639 --> 00:23:22.558
The husbands only come up
on weekends.

235
